\(H_0 : \beta_{aid22} = \beta_{loans22} = \beta_{library2022} = 0\)

\(H_0 : \beta_{i} = 0\)

\(H_1 : \beta_{i} \neq0\)

Reject \(H_0\) if p<0.05

The p-value <0.001 for all predictors, thus we reject \(H_0\). There is sufficient evidence to suggest that financial aid, Student loans, and Library circulations significantly predicts graduation numbers for the year 2022.

Brief interpretations for the slopes of the predictors.

\[Degree22=-397.5599+0.0704x_1+0.4457x_2+.0001x_3\]

For every one increase in financial aid, we expect an increase of 0.0704 in graduation numbers. NOTE: not as significant as other variables

For every one increase in student loans, we expect an increase of 0.0445 in graduation numbers.

For every one increase in Library circulation, we expect an increase of 0.0001 in graduation numbers.

Based on the model and finding how well the model fits the data, we can conclude the model does not fit the data well. Based on adjusted R square, 74% of the variance is explained by the model which is fairly good data fit.

Capstone_rate <- Capstone %>% 
  select(rate2022, rate2021, rate2020, rate2019, rate2018) %>% 
  na.omit()


colMeans(Capstone_rate, na.rm=TRUE)
rate2022 rate2021 rate2020 rate2019 rate2018 
48.28713 49.39604 50.35644 47.71287 46.54455 
df_rate <- Capstone_rate %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(`rate2022`, `rate2021`, `rate2020`, `rate2019`, `rate2018`),
               names_to = "year", values_to = "rates")
  

df_rate <- df_rate %>%
  mutate(Period = case_when(
    year %in% c("rate2018", "rate2019") ~ "PreCOVID",
    year %in% c("rate2020", "rate2021") ~ "During COVID",
    TRUE ~ "Post Covid"
  ))


anova_result1 <- aov(rates ~ Period, data = df_rate)
summary(anova_result1)
